1511
01:35:39.056 --> 01:35:42.686
So the first point I'd like to bring up is the small PCBU category,

1512
01:35:43.616 --> 01:35:45.816
which I believe some others have spoken to earlier this morning.

1513
01:35:46.186 --> 01:35:46.486
Mm-hmm.

1514
01:35:46.506 --> 01:35:49.886
The majority of Master Plumbers business members employ fewer than 20 workers,

1515
01:35:49.996 --> 01:35:53.056
meaning they would fall under the proposed small PCBU

1516
01:35:53.096 --> 01:35:56.896
category. In principle, reducing compliance complexity for small firms

1517
01:35:57.036 --> 01:36:00.896
is positive. But the reality is that many small plumbing businesses work

1518
01:36:00.976 --> 01:36:04.096
on construction sites controlled by larger principal contractors.

1519
01:36:04.656 --> 01:36:07.996
Those larger PCBUs are required to operate under more complex

1520
01:36:08.636 --> 01:36:11.436
worker participation structures and documentation systems.

1521
01:36:12.116 --> 01:36:15.576
This raises some key questions. How will these new small PCBU

1522
01:36:15.616 --> 01:36:19.296
provisions operate in multi-PCBU environments?

1523
01:36:20.056 --> 01:36:24.026
And will a subcontractor be expected to comply with principal contractors' full

1524
01:36:24.116 --> 01:36:26.056
system regardless of their size?

1525
01:36:26.856 --> 01:36:30.736
Without explicit guidance, there is a risk that the practical effect

1526
01:36:30.796 --> 01:36:34.296
of the small PCBU category will be minimal, as small

1527
01:36:34.316 --> 01:36:38.205
subcontractors may be still required to comply with the larger contractors'

1528
01:36:38.256 --> 01:36:42.036
systems. So this creates a bit of uncertainty and undermines, I think, the purpose

1529
01:36:42.096 --> 01:36:44.696
of that differentiated criteria in that regard.

1530
01:36:45.536 --> 01:36:48.136
It's also worth noting a cultural risk.

1531
01:36:49.016 --> 01:36:52.966
Subcontractors sometimes feel reluctant to report incidents on a principal

1532
01:36:52.996 --> 01:36:56.916
contractor's site for fear of reputational damage or loss of future work.

1533
01:36:57.356 --> 01:37:00.996
So clear reinforcement of those shared responsibilities across the

1534
01:37:01.016 --> 01:37:04.376
PCBUs would support a healthy reporting environment.

1535
01:37:05.346 --> 01:37:08.976
So our recommendation is that more clarity is provided for how worker participation

1536
01:37:08.996 --> 01:37:12.356
obligations apply in multi-PCBU environments,

1537
01:37:12.796 --> 01:37:14.936
particularly in the construction sector where this is very common.

1538
01:37:15.756 --> 01:37:19.716
Our second point is regard the shift towards prioritizing critical risks.

1539
01:37:20.416 --> 01:37:24.246
So the bill provides a clear focus on life-threatening hazards deemed critical

1540
01:37:24.316 --> 01:37:28.056
risks. Ideally, this will mean businesses spend less time on performative

1541
01:37:28.076 --> 01:37:31.256
compliance and can refocus attention on those key

1542
01:37:31.296 --> 01:37:35.236
hazards. However, the emphasis on critical risks may discourage

1543
01:37:35.276 --> 01:37:38.046
workers from raising issues that fall outside of that category.

1544
01:37:38.796 --> 01:37:42.712
So in the construction industry, there's a lot of those that-That

1545
01:37:42.812 --> 01:37:46.422
are quite considerable concerns that are not necessarily critical, but

1546
01:37:46.492 --> 01:37:46.852
may

1547
01:37:47.652 --> 01:37:49.912
result in significant long-term harm.

1548
01:37:50.012 --> 01:37:53.672
I'm talking about things like risks of slips and trips, manual

1549
01:37:53.712 --> 01:37:57.452
handling injuries, noise, vibration, fatigue, and mental health

1550
01:37:57.512 --> 01:38:01.292
concerns, which is a considerable issue in the construction industry.

1551
01:38:01.752 --> 01:38:02.152
So for,

1552
01:38:03.272 --> 01:38:05.812
these may not be critical, but they are very common.

1553
01:38:05.872 --> 01:38:09.712
And what we don't want is a system where the worker's level of protection depends

1554
01:38:09.772 --> 01:38:13.652
on the size of their employer. So, in this case, we recommend the

1555
01:38:14.032 --> 01:38:17.372
bill recognize the importance of identifying and managing non-critical but common

1556
01:38:17.452 --> 01:38:20.092
risks, particularly for small PCBUs.

1557
01:38:21.012 --> 01:38:23.532
Our third point is regarding ensuring small businesses understand their

1558
01:38:23.592 --> 01:38:27.112
obligations. For many small firms, the combination of running a business, managing

1559
01:38:27.252 --> 01:38:29.732
staff, meeting regulatory requirements can be overwhelming.

1560
01:38:30.432 --> 01:38:34.382
So introducing new categories and criteria, such as the small

1561
01:38:34.392 --> 01:38:38.132
PCBU criteria I touched on before, may increase that confusion unless

1562
01:38:38.172 --> 01:38:40.252
accompanied by clear, practical instruction.

1563
01:38:40.312 --> 01:38:43.612
So that's just a bit of a hark back to the point earlier about just that clear,

1564
01:38:44.292 --> 01:38:47.272
making sure those divisions are clear and those responsibilities are clear.

1565
01:38:48.512 --> 01:38:52.442
Just to touch on prequalification systems, we believe the

1566
01:38:52.492 --> 01:38:56.032
amendment bill provides an opportunity to actually address another key

1567
01:38:56.072 --> 01:38:59.912
challenge faced by our members, which relates to the inconsistent

1568
01:38:59.952 --> 01:39:03.732
prequalification requirements imposed by clients and principal contractors.

1569
01:39:04.412 --> 01:39:08.032
Many large firms use international frameworks, often from the UK and

1570
01:39:08.052 --> 01:39:11.162
Australia, which don't always align with New Zealand standards.

1571
01:39:11.592 --> 01:39:15.372
An example of this is differing PPE requirements for identical

1572
01:39:15.432 --> 01:39:17.272
tasks depending on the client,

1573
01:39:18.192 --> 01:39:22.152
the requirement to purchase additional equipment to satisfy site-specific policy,

1574
01:39:23.032 --> 01:39:24.712
rather than legislative necessity.

1575
01:39:25.412 --> 01:39:28.342
So this leads to increased administration workload and costs, particularly for

1576
01:39:28.432 --> 01:39:32.252
small businesses. And we would just recommend the development of a

1577
01:39:32.272 --> 01:39:35.972
nationally recognized health and safety prequalification framework to

1578
01:39:35.992 --> 01:39:37.992
provide consistency across the sector.

1579
01:39:39.012 --> 01:39:41.742
Finally, a note on enforcement and accountability.

1580
01:39:41.912 --> 01:39:45.192
We support strong enforcement for deliberate non-compliance.

1581
01:39:45.212 --> 01:39:48.822
Businesses that take health and safety seriously invest heavily in training,

1582
01:39:48.852 --> 01:39:50.292
equipment, and proper maintenance.

1583
01:39:50.912 --> 01:39:54.252
They should not be placed at a commercial disadvantage compared to those who cut

1584
01:39:54.292 --> 01:39:57.462
corners. In saying that, enforcement must be balanced with

1585
01:39:58.552 --> 01:40:02.332
education. So many small business owners underestimate the seriousness of their

1586
01:40:02.372 --> 01:40:05.722
obligations, and we recommend that WorkSafe increase proactive

1587
01:40:05.772 --> 01:40:09.552
engagement with high-risk trades so that business owners

1588
01:40:09.612 --> 01:40:13.502
understand both their responsibilities and the consequences of failing

1589
01:40:13.632 --> 01:40:17.492
to meet them. So in summary, to ensure the bill delivers

1590
01:40:17.572 --> 01:40:21.032
meaningful improvements, Master Plumbers recommends clarifying obligations for

1591
01:40:21.072 --> 01:40:24.462
small PCBUs operating in multi-PCBU environments,

1592
01:40:24.892 --> 01:40:28.872
ensuring non-critical but common risks are not deprioritized, providing

1593
01:40:28.912 --> 01:40:32.852
clear practical implementation guidance for small businesses, developing a

1594
01:40:32.892 --> 01:40:36.462
consistent health and safety prequalification framework, and strengthening

1595
01:40:36.532 --> 01:40:40.292
WorkSafe's proactive engagement with high-risk trades. Thank you for your time.

1596
01:40:40.472 --> 01:40:42.002
I welcome any questions from the committee.

1597
01:40:43.292 --> 01:40:45.352
Thanks very much. Honorable Phil Twyford.

1598
01:40:49.652 --> 01:40:50.552
We can't hear you, Phil.

1599
01:40:53.932 --> 01:40:54.192
Sorry.

1600
01:40:54.992 --> 01:40:55.272
Yeah.

1601
01:40:55.892 --> 01:40:59.472
How many workers in your industry, Lisa, would be

1602
01:40:59.912 --> 01:41:03.772
employed by businesses with 20 or fewer workers?

1603
01:41:04.732 --> 01:41:06.492
I would say the vast majority.

1604
01:41:06.832 --> 01:41:07.082
Mm-hmm.

1605
