I think the average size of a plumbing business in New Zealand is three

1606
01:41:11.312 --> 01:41:11.812
employees.

1607
01:41:11.872 --> 01:41:12.002
Yep.

1608
01:41:12.192 --> 01:41:15.792
And that's including often admin staff as well as the actual trade

1609
01:41:15.852 --> 01:41:19.192
practitioners. So I would say the vast majority of businesses would fall under that

1610
01:41:19.532 --> 01:41:20.542
20 individuals.

1611
01:41:20.582 --> 01:41:22.432
And how many thousand people would that be?

1612
01:41:23.532 --> 01:41:25.752
I wouldn't have the figures off the top of my head.

1613
01:41:25.972 --> 01:41:29.232
But yeah, I would certainly say the

1614
01:41:29.552 --> 01:41:30.052
majority

1615
01:41:30.892 --> 01:41:33.222
would be considered small businesses in that respect.

1616
01:41:33.252 --> 01:41:36.792
And how do you feel about all of those workers in your industry,

1617
01:41:37.252 --> 01:41:40.702
under this bill, no longer having substantive

1618
01:41:40.752 --> 01:41:43.592
protection for what you've described as the

1619
01:41:43.652 --> 01:41:47.492
common construction industries, like

1620
01:41:47.552 --> 01:41:51.252
slips and trips, manual handling injuries, fatigue and long

1621
01:41:51.352 --> 01:41:53.412
hours, mental health and suicide prevention?

1622
01:41:54.652 --> 01:41:57.752
Yeah, so that's a concern. That's why we have brought that one up.

1623
01:41:58.492 --> 01:42:02.272
Obviously, we don't want to focus on critical risks to take away from

1624
01:42:02.351 --> 01:42:04.372
that, so I think there needs to be a balance there.

1625
01:42:05.092 --> 01:42:08.931
And certainly in an industry like ours, some of what you would call not

1626
01:42:08.952 --> 01:42:11.312
critical risks can be critical in the long term.

1627
01:42:11.372 --> 01:42:15.282
So I think it's just that balance of acknowledging that for specific industries,

1628
01:42:15.352 --> 01:42:18.572
there might be some common risks that do need further

1629
01:42:18.892 --> 01:42:19.732
prioritization.

1630
01:42:20.492 --> 01:42:21.112
Yep. Thank you.

1631
01:42:21.212 --> 01:42:21.412
Yeah.

1632
01:42:22.492 --> 01:42:23.052
Grant McCallum.

1633
01:42:24.612 --> 01:42:26.152
Yeah. Hi. Thank you for your submission.

1634
01:42:26.932 --> 01:42:29.912
Just curious, so what sort of feedback do you get from your members about

1635
01:42:30.892 --> 01:42:34.872
dealing with the health and safety regime? I'm just curious, given your submission.

1636
01:42:35.432 --> 01:42:38.772
So I think we have a bit of a range. As I said,

1637
01:42:39.612 --> 01:42:43.192
we have our one-man bands. You might have just one trade professional working.

1638
01:42:43.232 --> 01:42:45.492
You've got obviously larger businesses as well.

1639
01:42:45.852 --> 01:42:49.632
So we do have a variety. Obviously, we are a

1640
01:42:49.712 --> 01:42:52.272
little bit skewed because our members go through a

1641
01:42:53.452 --> 01:42:55.702
quality assurance to become a Master Plumbers member.

1642
01:42:56.172 --> 01:42:59.332
So you'll generally find that our members are fulfilling those health and safety

1643
01:42:59.372 --> 01:43:02.962
obligations because that's a requirement to join our organization.

1644
01:43:03.332 --> 01:43:07.232
So I think we probably skew towards the more prepared and more onto

1645
01:43:07.312 --> 01:43:11.192
it in that respect. But in saying

1646
01:43:11.272 --> 01:43:15.092
that, we've had a dedicated health and safety person

1647
01:43:15.152 --> 01:43:16.692
who's liaised with businesses.

1648
01:43:16.702 --> 01:43:16.702
Yeah.

1649
01:43:16.712 --> 01:43:19.652
And there can be quite a bit of confusion as to

1650
01:43:20.952 --> 01:43:23.692
obligations, maintenance requirements, things like that.

1651
01:43:23.772 --> 01:43:26.622
So I think the want is there to do well.

1652
01:43:27.072 --> 01:43:30.892
Sometimes the navigation of the system is where people get a bit confused

1653
01:43:30.972 --> 01:43:33.092
and maybe might be missing something that they

1654
01:43:34.612 --> 01:43:38.552
do need to do. So in our case, we try to provide those resources.

1655
01:43:38.632 --> 01:43:39.732
But, certainly,

1656
01:43:40.692 --> 01:43:44.152
as I've said, proactive engagement from WorkSafe is always beneficial in

1657
01:43:44.492 --> 01:43:45.252
that case.

1658
01:43:45.472 --> 01:43:46.792
And just a quick sup if I may.

1659
01:43:46.832 --> 01:43:47.602
Last question. Yep.

1660
01:43:47.602 --> 01:43:48.182
Yeah, sure. And

1661
01:43:49.272 --> 01:43:53.012
your members, do they come to you actively seeking advice and

1662
01:43:53.552 --> 01:43:57.072
so forth? And do you find the advice you give, do you actually go to

1663
01:43:57.132 --> 01:44:00.032
WorkSafe and ask them to help you with the guidance you give?

1664
01:44:00.680 --> 01:44:04.410
So we have liaisons where they can come through us, it's part of

1665
01:44:04.440 --> 01:44:05.680
our member services.

1666
01:44:05.740 --> 01:44:05.910
Yep, cool.

1667
01:44:05.920 --> 01:44:09.900
And we do then liaise with the various-- We're almost like an in-between

1668
01:44:09.940 --> 01:44:13.860
there to see how we can help in that regard, and obviously in legal

1669
01:44:14.120 --> 01:44:17.600
requirements, we would have that checked over by someone with that professional

1670
01:44:17.620 --> 01:44:21.580
advice. So yeah, we do provide, in a sense, that medium person to

1671
01:44:21.640 --> 01:44:25.500
say, "Let's find out what your obligations are in that instance, and see

1672
01:44:25.540 --> 01:44:28.120
what resources we can use to find out that information."

1673
01:44:28.700 --> 01:44:29.020
Thank you.

1674
01:44:29.780 --> 01:44:32.439
Thanks very much, Lisa. I appreciate your time with us this morning.

1675
01:44:33.960 --> 01:44:37.820
Members, we're now inviting the Construction Health and Safety New Zealand Trust

1676
01:44:38.520 --> 01:44:39.820
to present to us. That's Chris

1677
01:44:41.580 --> 01:44:43.540
Alderson, Roger Macrae,

1678
01:44:44.340 --> 01:44:44.780
and

1679
01:44:45.960 --> 01:44:46.620
John Hemi.

1680
01:44:50.940 --> 01:44:51.700
Macrae, rather.

1681
01:44:57.729 --> 01:45:00.680
Good morning, Chris. We've got 10 minutes with you this morning, including any time

1682
01:45:00.720 --> 01:45:01.619
for questions. Over to you.

1683
01:45:02.920 --> 01:45:06.450
Hi. Good morning, everyone. Look, I'm Chris Alderson.

1684
01:45:06.520 --> 01:45:09.880
I'm the TE at Construction Health and Safety New Zealand Trust.

1685
01:45:10.860 --> 01:45:14.740
Roger was going to join us this morning, but I think he's just struggling to

1686
01:45:14.780 --> 01:45:15.360
get in. But-

1687
01:45:15.940 --> 01:45:16.140
Okay

1688
01:45:16.280 --> 01:45:17.560
... I'll push forward anyway.

1689
01:45:19.760 --> 01:45:23.610
So business is a charity, just dedicated to reducing harm in the New Zealand

1690
01:45:23.660 --> 01:45:24.700
construction sector.

1691
01:45:25.660 --> 01:45:27.520
We use evidence-based initiatives.

1692
01:45:29.040 --> 01:45:31.860
We've been working for about eight years, and they're recognized internationally as

1693
01:45:31.900 --> 01:45:34.860
leading practice. So we're created by industry, for industry.

1694
01:45:35.380 --> 01:45:39.320
And we're also the voice for small businesses, which I'll get into a little

1695
01:45:39.380 --> 01:45:39.470
bit,

1696
01:45:40.300 --> 01:45:41.840
that make up the majority of the sector.

1697
01:45:42.620 --> 01:45:44.900
So my background, I've been working

1698
01:45:46.280 --> 01:45:49.760
in, I guess, for over 35 years in New Zealand and

1699
01:45:49.800 --> 01:45:50.500
internationally.

1700
01:45:51.440 --> 01:45:55.360
I was implemented Fonterra's Critical Risk program in the sort

1701
01:45:55.400 --> 01:45:57.160
of mid-2014s, around there.

1702
01:45:58.120 --> 01:46:00.140
So I've done a lot of work in this area.

1703
01:46:01.380 --> 01:46:05.000
And I'm often working with boards and companies

1704
01:46:05.140 --> 01:46:06.640
on an advisory level as well.

1705
01:46:07.680 --> 01:46:11.460
So look, a note about the New Zealand construction industry.

1706
01:46:11.500 --> 01:46:13.790
Our industry is made up of many small businesses.

1707
01:46:13.840 --> 01:46:17.480
In fact, it's over 98% of the businesses have less than 20 workers,

1708
01:46:18.600 --> 01:46:22.440
and there's around about 85,000 businesses within the construction sector.

1709
01:46:24.120 --> 01:46:28.010
It's actually one of the most dangerous industries globally to work in.

1710
01:46:28.660 --> 01:46:32.630
Low barriers to entry, relatively low productivity, and very high levels of

1711
01:46:32.640 --> 01:46:36.560
business attrition as well. So construction workers suffer from nearly twice the

1712
01:46:36.600 --> 01:46:39.220
national average in poor physical and mental health conditions.

1713
01:46:39.460 --> 01:46:43.240
It's very rare to see a construction worker over the age of about 35 who isn't

1714
01:46:43.280 --> 01:46:47.040
dealing with a significant enduring physical or mental health condition.

1715
01:46:48.600 --> 01:46:51.480
Despite that, we've made a lot of progress over the past five years.

1716
01:46:51.580 --> 01:46:54.920
We've had 27% reduction in ACC claims since

1717
01:46:55.040 --> 01:46:58.920
2022, although around about 19% of that's probably due to business

1718
01:46:58.980 --> 01:47:02.640
activity climbing down, but there's definitely a 7% performance

1719
01:47:03.140 --> 01:47:04.560
improvement that we've made there.

1720
01:47:05.320 --> 01:47:08.720
And that's been really with a focused effort in reducing claims, most of them

1721
01:47:08.760 --> 01:47:10.060
musculoskeletal conditions.

1722
01:47:11.200 --> 01:47:14.880
We believe that this performance improvement is at risk, though, through this bill.

1723
01:47:15.180 --> 01:47:18.820
So the requirement that only organizations with 20 or more employees,

1724
01:47:19.240 --> 01:47:21.400
which is only 2% of our construction businesses,

1725
01:47:22.420 --> 01:47:26.260
also manage non-critical risks such as musculoskeletal harm, it

1726
01:47:26.280 --> 01:47:28.080
doesn't reflect the industry's burden of harm.

1727
01:47:28.300 --> 01:47:31.900
So the hard-won gains we've made would be threatened by a regulatory signal that

1728
01:47:31.940 --> 01:47:34.739
this type of harm is not to be a focus.

1729
01:47:34.820 --> 01:47:38.700
The existing act, consistent with international best practice legislation, already

1730
01:47:38.720 --> 01:47:42.520
includes requirements for businesses to manage risk proportionally, i.e., critical

1731
01:47:42.560 --> 01:47:42.740
risk.

1732
01:47:43.660 --> 01:47:46.780
Good construction businesses prioritize the prevention of serious harm and

1733
01:47:46.800 --> 01:47:47.389
fatalities.

1734
01:47:48.440 --> 01:47:52.300
Organizations experienced in critical risk management understand that there's kind

1735
01:47:52.320 --> 01:47:55.250
of two high-level complementary focal points.

1736
01:47:56.090 --> 01:47:59.840
The first is to identify the work-related hazards, which with the potential to

1737
01:47:59.900 --> 01:48:01.640
seriously or fatally injure a person.

1738
01:48:02.580 --> 01:48:06.280
And what you do then is you invest in strong physical controls to limit the

1739
01:48:06.320 --> 01:48:09.840
exposure. So controls that actually work regardless of the

1740
01:48:09.880 --> 01:48:13.580
human performing or not. On average in construction, we can do this

1741
01:48:13.640 --> 01:48:16.940
about 40% to 60% of the time. So there's a gap.

1742
01:48:17.239 --> 01:48:21.100
So again, between 40% to 60% of the time, we actually can't do that

1743
01:48:21.140 --> 01:48:24.940
because of the nature of the work. What we have to do then is really

1744
01:48:24.980 --> 01:48:28.450
support human performance, and this is about supporting humans to make the right

1745
01:48:28.520 --> 01:48:30.980
decisions about how the work can be carried on safely.

1746
01:48:32.000 --> 01:48:35.400
One of the issues we have is that when humans are impaired, their decision-making

1747
01:48:35.440 --> 01:48:39.040
ability is also degraded, and that's a really well-known and well-researched

1748
01:48:39.120 --> 01:48:40.660
factor in work-based fatalities.

1749
01:48:41.460 --> 01:48:45.280
So the primary reasons for impairment in the construction sector are, again, poor

1750
